<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><p data-start="0" data-end="943">In a Pushdown Automaton (PDA), the stack operates on a Last-In, First-Out (LIFO) principle, allowing access only to the topmost element. Transitions in a PDA can push multiple symbols onto the stack in a single operation but are typically defined to pop only one symbol at a time. This design choice aligns with the standard formal definition of PDAs, where each transition involves reading an input symbol (or ε for no input), popping one symbol from the top of the stack, and pushing a (possibly empty) string of symbols back onto the stack. This approach simplifies the computational model and maintains consistency in how the stack is manipulated. While it's possible to simulate the effect of popping multiple symbols by using a series of transitions or ε-moves, allowing multiple pops in a single transition would complicate the automaton's design and is not part of the conventional PDA definition. <span class="data-state="closed"><div class="relative inline-flex items-center"><a href="https://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/65489/can-you-pop-2-elements-at-a-time-in-a-pda?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="ml-1 inline-flex h-[22px] items-center rounded-xl bg-[#f4f4f4] px-2 text-[0.5em] font-medium text-token-text-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary !text-token-text-secondary uppercase hover:bg-token-text-primary hover:!text-token-main-surface-secondary dark:hover:bg-token-text-primary group"><span class="truncate">cs.stackexchange.com</span></a></div></span></p><div class="absolute h-[60px]"><button class="not-prose group/footnote mb-2 mt-3 flex w-fit items-center gap-1.5 rounded-xl border border-token-border-light bg-token-main-surface-primary py-2 hover:bg-token-main-surface-secondary pl-3 pr-2.5"><div class="flex items-center gap-0.5 text-sm font-medium">Sources</div><div class="flex flex-row-reverse"><div class="flex items-center 